<p><ent>Pique</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pique
<hw>Pique</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr.
<ets>piquer</ets>. See <er>Pike</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A feeling
of hurt, vexation, or resentment, awakened by a social slight or injury;
irritation of the feelings, as through wounded pride; stinging
vexation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men take up <qex>piques</qex> and displeasures.</q> <rj><qau>Dr.
H. More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wars had arisen . . . upon a personal <qex>pique</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Keenly felt desire; a longing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though it have the <qex>pique</qex>, and long,⟦br⟧
'Tis still for something in the wrong.</q>
<rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <def>In piquet, the right of
the elder hand to count thirty in hand, or to play before the adversary
counts one.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Displeasure; irritation; grudge; spite.</syn>
<usage> <er>Pique</er>, <er>Spite</er>, <er>Grudge</er>.
<xex>Pique</xex> denotes a quick and often transient sense of resentment
for some supposed neglect or injury, but it is not marked by
malevolence. <xex>Spite</xex> is a stronger term, denoting settled ill
will or malice, with a desire to injure, as the result of extreme
irritation. <xex>Grudge</xex> goes still further, denoting cherished and
secret enmity, with an unforgiving spirit. A <xex>pique</xex> is usually
of recent date; a <xex>grudge</xex> is that which has long subsisted;
<xex>spite</xex> implies a disposition to cross or vex
others.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pique</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pique
<hw>Pique</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Piqued</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Piquing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>piquer</ets>. See <er>Pike</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To wound
the pride of; to sting; to nettle; to irritate; to fret; to offend; to
excite to anger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Pique</qex> her, and soothe in turn.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To excite to action by causing resentment or
jealousy; to stimulate; to prick; <as>as, to <ex>pique</ex> ambition, or
curiosity</as>.</def> <rj><au>Prior.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To pride or value; -- used reflexively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men . . . <qex>pique</qex> themselves upon their skill.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To offend; displease; irritate; provoke; fret;
nettle; sting; goad; stimulate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pique</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Pique
<hw>Pique</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To cause annoyance or
irritation.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Every verse hath something in it that
<xex>piques</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Tatler.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Piqueer</ent>⟦br⟧
